The ballot measures Californians weighed in on this month were a grab bag of reforms. 

Though the proposals varied, the results showed a clear divide: L.A. County and San Francisco Bay Area voters are far apart from the rest of the state on most issues. https://t.co/QJCcqrbMos

Wondering how your Los Angeles County neighborhood voted on Prop. 22? 

Take a look at this map, made by @ryanmenezes:  https://t.co/1M6yvGg2hJ
. https://t.co/emOjoyWiiL

While the opposition campaign said it was pushing for greater benefits for workers, the yes campaign countered that it was providing “historic” new benefits — even though the new benefits are weaker than those provided to employees by state law.  https://t.co/2EwaFEuTp0 https://t.co/4Sh7iqDkH4

Voters who are undecided tend to break to the no side of ballot measures.

But while a yes vote in Prop 22’s case maintained workers’ current status as independent contractors, a no vote would have altered drivers’ employment status. https://t.co/2EwaFEuTp0 https://t.co/KZhBLnPcUD

Uber and Lyft threatened to leave California or raise prices and cut jobs if Prop. 22 was voted down. 

Some suggest voters may have supported the measure because they feared the consequences its failure would bring to customers and drivers. https://t.co/2EwaFEuTp0

Facing an uphill battle, gig economy companies set a spending record, pouring more than $200 million into the ballot initiative. 

They saturated TV and digital ad space. They bombarded workers and customers with in-app notifications and emails. https://t.co/2EwaFEuTp0 https://t.co/4PiDX49chI
